JAVA VARIABLES INTERVIEW QUESTIONS:

1. What are variables in Java? Types?
👉 Answer (spoken):
Variables are named memory locations used to store data. In Java, we have three types: local variables, instance variables, and static variables.
👉 Technical Example:
class Student {
    static String college = "ABC"; // static
    int id; // instance

    void display() {
        int marks = 90; // local
    }
}
👉 Real-world:
Static → shared (company name)
Instance → per object (user data)
Local → temporary (method calculation)
Variable type determines its lifecycle, scope, and memory allocation.

2. Difference between instance and static variables
👉 Answer:

Instance	                    Static
Per object	                Shared
Stored in heap	Stored in method area
Access via object	Access via class
class Test {
    int a = 10; // instance
    static int b = 20; // static
}

Changing static variable affects all objects.
Static variables belong to class, not object

3. Why local variables don’t have default values?
👉 Answer:
Because they are stored in stack and Java enforces initialization to avoid garbage values.
int x;
System.out.println(x); // Compile-time error
👉 Real-world:
Prevents unpredictable bugs in calculations
👉 Follow-up:
Why instance variables have defaults?
Java prioritizes safety over convenience for local variables.

4. Where are variables stored in memory?
👉 Answer:
Local → Stack
Instance → Heap
Static → Method Area
👉 Technical Example:
int x = 10; // stack
Student s = new Student(); // object in heap
👉 Follow-up:
What happens when stack overflows?
👉 Impress line:
“Stack handles execution, heap handles object storage.

5. What is final variable?
👉 Answer:
A final variable cannot be reassigned once initialized.
👉 Technical Example:
final int x = 10;
x = 20; // error
👉 Tricky Case:
final List<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();
list.add(10); // allowed
👉 Real-world:
Constants like API keys
👉 Follow-up:
Difference between final and immutability?
👉 Impress line:
“final prevents reassignment, not object modification.”

6. What is effectively final variable? (Java 8)
👉 Answer:
A variable that is not declared final but never modified.
👉 Example:
int x = 10;
Runnable r = () -> System.out.println(x); // allowed
👉 Tricky:
If you modify x → compilation error
👉 Follow-up:
Why required in lambda?
👉 Impress line:
“Lambda captures only effectively final variables for thread safety.”

7. Can we declare static local variables in Java?
👉 Answer:
No, Java does not allow static local variables.
👉 Tricky Example:
void test() {
    static int x = 10; // ❌ error
}
👉 Reason:
Local variables belong to stack frame, static belongs to class
👉 Follow-up:
Why allowed in C++ but not Java?
👉 Impress line:
“Java avoids complexity of static state inside stack frames.”


8. What happens if we don’t initialize instance variable?
👉 Answer:
Java assigns default values.
👉 Defaults:
int → 0
boolean → false
object → null
👉 Example:
class Test {
    int x;
    void show() {
        System.out.println(x); // 0
    }
}
👉 Follow-up:
Why no default for local?
👉 Impress line:
“Default initialization is JVM responsibility, not compiler.”


9. Difference between final, static final, and constant
👉 Answer:
Type	Meaning
final	 cannot change
static final	 constant shared across class
👉 Example:
static final double PI = 3.14;
👉 Real-world:
Used in utility classes
👉 Follow-up:
Where constants stored?
👉 Impress line:
“static final variables are compile-time constants if primitive or String.”

10. What is variable shadowing?
👉 Answer:
When local variable hides instance variable.
👉 Example:
class Test {
    int x = 10;
    void show() {
        int x = 20;
        System.out.println(x); // 20
    }
}
👉 Fix:
System.out.println(this.x); // 10
👉 Follow-up:
Why avoid shadowing?
👉 Impress line:
“Shadowing reduces code readability and increases bugs.”

11. What is transient variable?
👉 Answer:
Used to skip variable during serialization.
👉 Example:
transient int password;
👉 Real-world:
Sensitive data like passwords not saved
👉 Follow-up:
What is serialization?
👉 Impress line:
“transient improves security in object persistence.”

12. What is volatile variable?
👉 Answer:
Ensures visibility of changes across threads.
👉 Example:
volatile boolean flag = true;
👉 Real-world:
Stopping a thread safely
👉 Follow-up:
volatile vs synchronized?
👉 Impress line:
“volatile guarantees visibility, not atomicity.”

13. What is default value of variables?
👉 Answer:
Only instance and static variables get defaults.
👉 Example:
int x; // 0
boolean b; // false
👉 Follow-up:
Why String default null?
👉 Impress line:
“Reference types default to null, not empty objects.”

14. What is var keyword (Java 10)?
👉 Answer:
Allows type inference for local variables.
👉 Example:
var x = 10; // int
var name = "Komal"; // String
👉 Tricky:
Cannot use without initialization
👉 Follow-up:
Can var be used for instance variables?
👉 Impress line:
“var improves readability but does not make Java dynamically typed.”

15. Can we declare variables without type?
👉 Answer:
No, Java is statically typed (except var inference)
👉 Tricky:
var x; // ❌ error
👉 Follow-up:
Difference between dynamic typing?
👉 Impress line:
“Java enforces strong typing at compile time.”

16. What is constant pool in Java?
👉 Answer:
Memory area where String literals are stored
👉 Example:
String s1 = "Java";
String s2 = "Java"; // same reference
👉 Follow-up:
What about new String()?
👉 Impress line:
“String pool improves memory efficiency.”

17. What is variable scope?
👉 Answer:
Region where variable is accessible
👉 Types:
Local
Instance
Static
👉 Example:
if(true) {
    int x = 10;
}
// x not accessible here
👉 Follow-up:
What is block scope?
👉 Impress line:
“Smaller scope improves maintainability.”

19. What is type casting in variables?
👉 Answer:
Converting one data type into another
👉 Example:
int x = (int) 10.5; // explicit
👉 Real-world:
Data conversion from DB to API
👉 Follow-up:
Implicit vs explicit?
👉 Impress line:
“Explicit casting may cause data loss.”

Scenario Based Questions:
1. What will be the output? (String Pool Trap)
String s1 = "Java";
String s2 = "Java";
String s3 = new String("Java");
System.out.println(s1 == s2);
System.out.println(s1 == s3);
System.out.println(s1.equals(s3));
👉 Answer (spoken):
First is true, second is false, third is true.
👉 Explanation:
s1 & s2 → same string pool reference
s3 → new object in heap
equals() compares content
👉 Real-world:
Comparing user input strings vs stored constants
👉 Follow-up:
How to force string pool usage?
👉 Impress line:
“String pool avoids duplicate objects for memory optimization.”

2. What will be the output? (Final + Object)
final List<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();
list.add(10);
list.add(20);
System.out.println(list);
👉 Answer:
[10, 20]
👉 Explanation:
final prevents reassignment, not modification
👉 Follow-up:
Can we reassign list?
👉 Impress line:
“final reference ≠ immutable object.”













